  <span id="freeText4254018849745101828" style="display:none">You know how Goodreads has the Spoilers box you can check? I clearly need one for Full Of Despair Over The Future, And That Is Clearly Impacting This Book "Review." Honestly I'm surprised Goodreads doesn't already have something for this. <br /><br />For the first time I became depressed while reading one of the Discworld books. <br /><br />I don't mean a misty eyed "Terry Pratchett is dead, and there will never be another new Discworld book to surprise and delight me" sort of sadness. I'm talking about soul crushing depressed. <br /><br />Because the thing that causes me to reread Pratchett's books over and over are the well crafted and witty personifications of silly human behavior stretched to extremes, which are then batted around by Pratchett's wit like a catnipped soaked squeaky mouse by an excited kitten.<br /><br />But this time, despite the comforting presence of gargoyles, werewolves, dwarves, Foul Ron, and The Importance Of Always Having A Potato...the real world snuck in. I've read The Truth before and was delighted the whole way through, but that was when the world made sense. Today what was silliness has become disturbingly reflective of the America's current political system. Tyranny is coming, and not in the educated and well informed style of Vetinari, but in the greedy destructive hands of those who care nothing for this country, but only for their own pockets. <br /><br />Pratchett was an amazing writer. His works are one of the few (if not only) books that are original, witty, and well crafted enough for my oozing angst to find a logical structure to process unheard of in my lifetime political turmoil...and for the very same books to, when I'm in a different mood, be relaxing, funny and relaxing. Nuances of brilliance. <br /><br />Today, and for as many tomorrows as I need to, I'm going to try and hold out hope that the end of The Truth is predictive of the end of the next four years. That after some "unpleasantness" we can dust ourselves off, find a new balance, and toddle off to a more hopeful future. <br /><br />So all of this was really more of a review of my current pessimist, frightened, angry and despairing mood, and not so much of the book. The book is very good, and actually quite funny, and you should read it. <br /><br /></span>
